Mary de Boer

Bio

Mary de Boer, MSc., is a global public health professional with more than 13 years experience working with local and international non-governmental organizations and bilateral donors. Her work has taken her to Latin America, Sub-Saharan Africa, Central Asia, and South Asia. Mary’s current focus is on implementation science, examining the lessons learned from an ongoing randomized controlled trial of a maternal nutrition intervention – Balanced Energy Protein (BEP) supplementation – in rural northwestern Bangladesh. Mary has experience in both qualitative and quantitative research methods, economic analysis, program design, training development and delivery, and leadership and management.

Education

Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health | Baltimore, MD

Ph.D. in International Health - Human Nutrition | August 2022 - May 2026 (expected)

The London School of Economics | London, UK

M.Sc. in Health, Community and Development | September 2009 - December 2010

Pomona College | Claremont, CA

B.A. in English Literature; Premedical Sciences track | August 2003 - May 2007

Experience

USAID | Foreign Service Officer | August 2011 - Present

National Cancer Institute: Center to Reduce Cancer Health Disparities | Health Communications Fellow | January 2011 - July 2011

MEA Foundation Buguruni | Program Evaluator | July 2008 - May 2009

Swarthmore College | Undergraduate Writing Program Coordinator | August 2007 - June 2008

Pomona College | Writing Fellow and Teaching Assistant | August 2004 - June 2007

Cleveland Clinic Foundation | Summer Undergraduate Research Program | June 2005 - August 2005
